-- Hong Kong's Stock Index Rebounds From Three-Month Low; Cnooc Climbs on Oil
-- B y   H a n n y   W a n
-- 2010-12-29T08:43:09Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-29/hong-kong-s-stock-index-rebounds-from-three-month-low-cnooc-climbs-on-oil.html
Hong Kong  stocks  rose, lifting the
benchmark index from a three-month low, as oil producers climbed
along with crude prices and banks gained on prospects for higher
earnings.  Cnooc Ltd., China’s No. 1 offshore oil producer, advanced
2.6 percent. China Construction Bank Corp., the nation’s No. 2
bank by market value, gained 2.4 percent.  China Railway Group
Ltd.  advanced 1.8 percent after the nation’s biggest
construction company by total assets said it won 16 projects.  “Resources stocks, including producers of oil and other
fuel, are in favor because of the seasonal factor,” said  Steve Tse , a research manager at BEA Union Investment Management in
Hong Kong. “Chinese banks will show earnings growth for this
year. However, given China’s tightening policies, they’re likely
to be affected” in 2011.  The  Hang Seng Index  increased 1.5 percent to close at
22,969.30, rebounding from yesterday’s close at the lowest level
since Oct. 4. The  Hang Seng China Enterprises Index  of so-called
H shares of Chinese companies climbed 1.6 percent to 12,508.52.  The Hang Seng Index has gained 5 percent this year, after
rallying 52 percent in 2009, on speculation growth in corporate
profits would counter China’s steps to curb property-price
inflation, Europe’s debt crisis, and concern about the pace of
the U.S. economic recovery.  Shares in the gauge trade at an average 14.4 times
estimated earnings, compared with 17.2 times at the beginning of
this year.  Cnooc advanced 2.6 percent to HK$18.46.  PetroChina Co. , the
nation’s largest oil and gas producer, increased 2.3 percent to
HK$9.99.  Oil Futures  Crude oil futures gained 0.5 percent to $91.49 yesterday,
after rising to $91.88, the highest price since October 2008, on
Dec. 27 in intraday trading. Futures slid 0.1 percent in after-
hours electronic trading in New York as of 4:14 p.m. Hong Kong
time today.  Construction Bank rose 2.4 percent to HK$6.84. Bank of
Communications Co., China’s fifth-largest lender by market value,
advanced 1.7 percent to HK$7.82.  China’s banking industry may have 800 billion yuan ($121
billion) in profit this year, the China Securities Journal said,
citing Yang Zaiping, vice chairman of the nation’s banking
association.  That’s higher than the 668.4 billion yuan of profit for the
nation’s banking industry in 2009, according to data from the
China Banking Regulatory Commission.  China Petroleum  Cheung Kong (Holdings) Ltd. , Hong Kong’s No. 2 developer by
market value, advanced 2.8 percent to HK$121.60.  Hutchison
Whampoa Ltd. , with operations in industries including ports and
telecommunications, rose 1.4 percent to HK$81.  The companies plan a residential-commercial development in
Chongqing, China, with a total investment of 1.9 billion yuan.
The two companies are paying 1.3 billion yuan for the site,
about 132,471 square meters, Hutchison said.  China Railway Group advanced 1.8 percent to HK$5.61 after
saying it won 16 projects worth a combined 20.5 billion yuan.
The company also agreed to buy a company that builds airports,
roads and bridges from its parent for 372.9 million yuan.  China Petroleum & Chemical Corp., the nation’s largest oil
refiner and known as Sinopec, climbed 2.1 percent to HK$7.34.
The company acquired a 40 percent stake in Repsol YPF SA’s
Brazilian unit, according to a statement by the Madrid-based
company. Sinopec’s investment values the unit at $17.8 billion,
Repsol said.  Separately, Sinopec’s parent China Petrochemical Corp. may
post 1.96 trillion yuan in sales this year, a 41 percent
increase from 2009, the China Daily reported, citing the company.  All but one stock rose among the 45 constituents of the
Hang Seng Index. Its futures gained 1.6 percent to 23,006.  To contact the reporter on this story:
